name: 1-4 Suffolk Street: Uni of Notre Dame & G.K Chesterton
description: Built for the United Universities Club, 1-4 Suffolk Street  is now home to the University of Notre Dame and its G.K Chesterton Collection. Visitors will be able to enjoy both this Edwardian listed building and the unique collection within.

name: 1.20 Oxo Tower Wharf
description: Unit 1.20 is one of 25 workshop and retail units in Oxo Tower Wharf and overlooks the courtyard towards the Bargehouse building from the first floor walkway. It is a multi-purpose space used as a workshop, showroom and teaching space.
address: Unit 1.20, The Courtyard, Oxo Tower Wharf, Bargehouse Street

name: 10 Tollgate Drive
description: Part of Austin Vernon & Parters designed estate completed 1966, 10 Tollgate Drive is range style house, refurbished in 2008 by Powell Tuck Associates,  owners are Angus and Sarah Shepherd, Angus is Director at Powell Tuck Associates.

name: 1923 Northern Line Extension stations
description: A tour that contrasts the before and after of the architecture of the 1922 Northern line extension, examining the impact on the existing terminus at Golders Green as well as the new station architectural vernacular created by Stanley Heaps
address: Golders Green Underground Station, North End Road, NW11 7RN

name: 195 Mare Street
description: 195 Mare Street

name: 25 Cannon Street
description: Situated adjacent to St. Paulâ€™s Cathedral, our reworking of this six-storey neo-classical building has created 116,000 sq ft of high-quality office space, three levels of communal terraces and a large new garden designed by Tom Stuart-Smith

name: 373 Euston Road, Birkbeck College
description: The refurbishment and roof extension of 7-storey building at 373 Euston Road to accommodates a 180-person lecture theatre, high-quality classrooms, as well as formal and informal co-learning spaces.

name: 8 Gransden Road
description: A basement, rear extension and courtyard garden to an end of terrace Victorian house. The design focusses on natural materials, expression of structure and craftsmanship, with high levels of daylight.

name: 80 Mallard Place, Twickenham
description: This is a beautiful house in Eric Lyons' last SPAN development from 1982

name: 82-83 Margaret Street
description: 82-83 Margaret Street was originally constructed as a convent in 1914, and contains the Grade II listed All Saints Convent Chapel to the rear.

name: 8a Belsize Court Garages
description: Originally a late 19C coachman's living quarters and stable, this mews house combines an award-winning architect's studio and spacious light-filled maisonette after a 2-phase carbon-reducing retrofit.

name: A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage
description: Ruskinian walk from RIBA award-winning Chiswick Business Park, Gunnersbury Triangle Nature Reserve through South Acton Estate, birthplace of artist Patrick Caulfield; Woodlands Park Ice House; to home of Wm Willett, of Daylight Saving Time
address: Building 3, Chiswick Business Park, 566 Chiswick High Road, W4 5YA

name: A Tale of Two Cities: North Kensington Walking Tour
description: This walking tour maps out North Kensington's evolution from 1800s Victorian middle-class suburbia, to the vibrant and diverse inner London neighbourhood it is today, revealing a multi-faceted, contradictory and oft misunderstood area .
address: St John's Church, 152 Lansdowne Crescent, W11 2NN

name: Abbey Mills Pumping Station
description:
Abbey Mills pumping station 'A', built by engineer Joseph Bazalgette, Edmund Cooper and architect Charles Driver. Built between 1865 and 1868 it is described as the cathedral of sewage.
Follow this link to book: https://bit.ly/abbeymills

name: Aga Khan Centre
description: The Aga Khan Centre, designed by Pritzker prize winning architect Fumihiko Maki, houses the UK institutions of the Aga Khan Development Network. A unique feature are its six gardens inspired by different regions of the Muslim world.
address: Aga Khan Centre, 10 Handyside Street, N1C 4DN

name: All Saints Carshalton
description: 12C south aisle and former chancel. Blomfield nave, chancel, baptistry. Kempe glass, Bodley reredos and screen, spectacular Comper decorations, monuments and brasses, award-winning lighting scheme, fine modern benches.

name: All Saints, Foots Cray
description: Medieval church (c1330) amended 1863 by Hakewill and retaining original elements such as windows and an arch to the north aisle, and altar tomb of Sir Simon de Vaughan.

name: Allies and Morrison Open Studio
description: Three buildings - one concrete, one Victorian, one timber - have been designed, adapted, restored and extended by Allies and Morrison to create the compact, integrated campus of studio space that the practice calls home.

name: Ancient Livery Companies in the City of London
description:
On this walk we shall discover some of the livery companies, learn about their ancient traditions and ceremonies, which are repeated every year. Also hear about  their important role in the City.
Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: Arbeit - Trowbridge Gardens
description: On Saturday 9th September, from 12 noon to 5pm, Arbeit will be opening Trowbridge Gardens to the public, with access to gardens and creative workspaces, and a free to attend exhibition and workshops.

name: BT Tower
description: An enduring, distinctive feature of the London skyline for the last 54 years, this is a rare opportunity for members of the public to visit the famous revolving floor, 158m above the capital. After the flight the guests can watch a history of the BT Tower film in our auditorium.

name: Barking Abbey with St Margaret's Church
description: 666AD Grade I listed church with a Curfew Tower, Chapel of Holy Rood with 12C Rood Stone amongst monuments, art and ruins. Artworks by George Jack & Walker Organ (1914). Captain Cook was noted to have married here. There is also a tea shop.
address: The Broadway, North Street, Barking, Essex, IG11 8AS

name: Beating the Bounds
description: Setting off from the Festival of Britain site we cover icons of the South Bank before heading into the back streets to see different types of social housing. We travel over to Bankside to see an overview of the historic and contemporary.
address: By the London Eye Pier, The Queen's Walk, SE1 7PB

name: Benjamin Franklin House
description: Grade I listed Georgian house, the only surviving home of Benjamin Franklin, retaining many original features including central staircase, lathing, 18th Century panelling, stoves, windows, fittings and beams.

name: Bethlehem Chapel
description: An independent Calvinistic chapel on the east side of Church Terrace in Richmond, London. Built in 1797, the small 1-storey stuccoed building is Grade II* listed. It still has its original galleried interior with pews and pulpit.
address: Bethlehem Chapel, Church Terrace, Richmond upon Thames , TW10 6SE

name: Bethlem Royal Hospital
description: Guided walking tours of the grounds of Bethlem Royal Hospital, taking in the Hospital's historic Chapel, its beautiful grounds, Bethlem Museum of the Mind, and Bethlem Gallery. Open House 2023 tours delivered as part of This is Croydon, London Borough of Culture, with the support of Mayor of London and Croydon Council.
address: Bethlem Museum of the Mind, Beckenham, BR3 3BX

name: Billingsgate Roman House & Baths
description: Some of London's best Roman remains, comprising late 2C house with a 3C bath house built within its courtyard. First discovered in 1848.

name: Boston Manor House
description: Boston Manor House is a Jacobean House built for Lady Mary Reade in 1623 and later owned by the Clitherow family from the 1670s until the 1920s.  The House is now open to the public with free entry six days a week. Its beautifully restored historic interiors, including breath-taking original ornate plasterwork, are joined by two community exhibition galleries, meeting rooms and an attractive modern cafÃ©
address: Boston Manor House, Boston Manor Road, Brentford, TW8 9JX

name: Brandon Centre
description: West Kentish Town Conservation Area. Brandon Cadbury, (of the famous philanthropic chocolatiers) was so impressed with our founder and young peoples services he donated our building. As a thank you, we named the charity after him in 1984.
address: 26 Prince of Wales Road , Kentish Town, NW5 3LG

name: Brentford Canal Toll House and Gauging Lock
description: Single-storey canal toll house (1911) where tolls were collected for passing through the lock. Grand Junction Canal connected the Thames at Brentford to the Industrial Midlands in 1794 at the height of the industrial revolution.
address: Grand Union Canal Walk, Brentford, TW8 8GA

name: Brentham Garden Suburb
description: Britain's first co-partnership garden suburb, first houses built 1901. Parker and Unwin's plan introduced 1907, mainly Arts and Crafts style; fascinating social history.
address: The Brentham Club, 38 Meadvale Road, W5 1NP

name: Brixton Windmill
description: A wonderful reminder of Brixton's rural past and inner London's last working mill. Built in 1816 by the Ashby family who produced flour until 1934.  Restored to working order 2011.

name: Bromley Archives- Bromley Central Library
description: Take a tour around Bromley Archives. The archive store itself is normally closed to the public and visitors will be allowed access within this space and a look at some of the items that we have in our collection.
address: Bromley Historic Collections, Bromley Central Library, High Street

name: Bush Theatre - Backstage Tours
description: Explore the Bush Theatre, West Londonâ€™s home of new writing. Get a behind the scenes look at our fifty-year history, including how over 2016 we transformed our 128-year-old building into an accessible and sustainable modern theatre.

name: Canada House
description: Canada's diplomatic home in the United Kingdom, the revitalised Canada House serves as a showcase for the very best of Canadian art and design in the 21C.

name: Carshalton Water Tower and Historic Gardens
description: Early 18C Grade II listed building incorporating plunge bath with Delft tiles, orangery, saloon and pump chamber with part-restored water wheel. Hermitage and sham bridge in grounds.

name: Centre Court Shopping Centre, Wimbledon
description: Centre Court is in the process of being transformed into a unique mixed-use local community hub. There's a new community-facing entrance, a sliding roof and a range of new uses including a roof-top farm, gym, restaurants, climbing wall etc.

name: Chartered Accountants' Hall
description: Late Victorian neo-Baroque building with modern-style 1970 extensions supporting 5 storeys of recently refurbished offices over the Great Hall.

name: Chiswick House and Gardens
description: Chiswick House and Gardens is one of the most glorious examples of 18th-century British architecture and landscaping with over 300 years of discovery, inspiration and delight.
address: Chiswick House and Gardens , Burlington Ln, W4 2RP

name: Christ Church
description: The church is designed in the Gothic style, with a semicircular barrel-vaulted ceiling, a highly carved chancel screen and magnificent stained glass windows, notably the large West window, depicting Christ the King enthroned in heaven.

name: Church of St Mary the Blessed Virgin
description: Founded in 11C, with Jacobean memorial c1615. Burial site of 5 Archbishops of Canterbury.
address: Addington Village Road, Addington, Croydon, CR0 5AS

name: City & Guilds of London Art School
City Hall
description: The sustainable new headquarters of the Mayor of London and London Assembly located in the Royal Docks, Newham.  The docks are re-emerging as a commercial and cultural hub, and an exciting new waterfront.

name: City Information Centre
description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's.

name: City Mill Pool Street
address: City Mill Pool Street, Pool Street, E20 2AF

name: City of Westminster Archives Centre
description: Modern red brick building purpose-built to house the City of Westminster's historic records. Opportunity to visit the conservation studio and see treasures of the archives.

name: Cressingham Gardens
description: Low-rise high density estate located next to Brockwell Park. Innovative design with pioneering architectural elements & echoing natural topography. Under threat of demolition by Lambeth council. Tours provided of estate and rotunda.
address: Cressingham Gardens Rotunda, Tulse Hill , SW2 2QG

name: Croydon Minster
description: Medieval style church rebuilt by Sir George Gilbert Scott after 1867 fire. Tower & south porch are 15C. Large nave with open timber-work roof leads to chancel dominated by superb stained glass window & rich alabaster reredos.

name: Cycling Book Loversâ€™ London
description: A bicycle tour of public libraries and bookshops from Bloomsbury to the East End celebrating the institutions which keep books circulating and the buildings which bring readers and writers together. Over the course of the tour, weâ€™ll see how architects working across a range of building styles express the ideals of their bookish institutions.

name: Dorich House Museum
description: The former studio home of the sculptor Dora Gordine and her husband the Hon. Richard Hare, a scholar of Russian art and literature. 1930s house over four floors including a flat roof terrace and views of Richmond Park.
address: Dorich House Museum, 67 Kingston Vale, SW15 3RN

name: Dr Johnson's House
description: Fine example of an early 5-floor Queen Anne town house with original panelling, open staircase and unique 'swinging panels' on the open-plan first floor. Johnson compiled his famous 'Dictionary of the English Language' (1755)  here.

name: Ealing South Walk
description: This is an attractive walk through Ealing south of Uxbridge Road. It passes Sir John Soane's Pitzhanger Manor, Ealing Studios and many attractive Georgian and early Victorian streets of Ealing's early development.

name: Eames Fine Art
description: A great example of the rich evolution of Londonâ€™s buildings; from noxious leather treatment warehouse complete with sloping floors, winch poles and loading platforms to a stylish hidden Art Collectorâ€™s Studio in the space of 150 years.

name: East Croydon Community Organisation
description: Historic walking tour of East Croydon led by a native. Those who come along are welcome to contribute their memories.  Marvel at one of the oldest electricity sub-stations in Croydon. Tour ends at the iconic One Croydon, the "Thru'penny Bit" office block designed by Seifert in the 1960s.  Join us for a drink afterwards in a Victorian hostelry.
address: The Cricketers, 107 Addiscombe Road, Croydon, CR0 6SG

name: East Greenwich Fire Station
description: A striking 1980s fire station featuring an expressive drill tower.
address: East Greenwich Fire Station, 325 Woolwich Road, SE7 7RF

name: Eastcote Walking Tour
description: Discover the fascinating history of Eastcote and its surroundings, focused on how the landscape has changed, from the exclusively agricultural area to the today's modern suburb, revealing some of the oldest local buildings and their stories
address: Eastcote Station, Field End Road, Pinner, HA5 1QZ

name: Edmonton - an Edwardian North London suburb
description: Edmonton has been described as a working class suburb but there are now signs of growing affluence, a result of regeneration and some might say the neighbourhood is ripe for gentrification. The walk will explore a variety of neighbourhoods.
address: Entrance to Silver Street Station (Platform 1, London bound side)

name: Emanuel School
description:
Former Royal Patriotic orphanage, converted to school 1883, with 1896 additions and other developments. High Victorian style with stained glass by Moira Forsyth. Set in 12 acres.

In 2022 the building celebrates its 150th anniversary.
address: Battersea Rise (entrance via bridge over the railway on Spencer Park)

name: Embassy of the Republic of Poland
description: Georgian townhouse built by Robert and James Adam in the years 1776-1780 is a fine example of the Adam style of Neoclassical interior design. Seat of the Polish Embassy in London since 1921, it also houses a collection of Polish artworks.

name: Exploring Spring Grove Isleworth
description: Centred on Spring Grove House, once Sir Joseph Banks home the 1850s vision was for John Taylor Jnr designed grand villas.  Today's  wider architecture includes a former college by John Norton & P Massey plus quirky arts & crafts properties.
address: Forecourt, Isleworth Railway Station, London Road, Isleworth, TW7 4BX

name: Ferry Lane Estate
description: A tour round the estate, with visits to residents' homes, information on the original design principles, tenancy types & history plus an opportunity to appreciate the setting with the River Lea bordering the estate. Approx 90 mins.
address: Nearest property 1 Reedham Close, Ferry Lane Estate, N17 9PX

name: Founders' Hall
description: Begun in 1985, our fifth Hall is constructed of traditional materials in a manner which is in keeping with this historic part of the City.

name: Frederick W Paine Funeral Directors
description: The town's oldest firm of funeral directors has conducted funerals from these premises since 1908. The original interior is Grade II listed. The building also contains the Frederick W Paine Museum and the firm's archive.
address: 24 Old London Road, Kingston upon Thames, KT2 6QG

name: Freemasons' Hall
description: The current building, the third on the site, was built between 1927-1933 in the Art Deco style, as a memorial to the 3,225 Freemasons who died in World War I. It is a Grade II* listed building, both internally and externally.
address: Freemasons' Hall, 60 Great Queen Street, WC2B 5AZ

name: From Forest to Morris: A walk around Walthamstow
description: A walk around historic Walthamstow showing how this unique area grew from a village into a thriving suburb, its social history and the variety of buildings that can be found where Epping Forest meets William Morris.
address: Outside Costa Coffee at Walthamstow Central Station 5 Station Approac

name: From Old Oak to White City
description: The walk will explore four different types of housing north and south of the A40, which reveal much about the history of social housing in London. It will also include a rare chance to visit an award-winning community garden.
address: East Acton Tube Station,, Erconwald Street, W12 0BP

name: Fulham Road Picturehouse
description: Fulham Road Picturehouse takes us back to the glory days of 1930s period glamour in this stunning listed building. Earle Architects (who did a fantastic job with Bromley Picturehouse) have helped us revive Fulham Road to its former vintage
address: Fulham Road Picturehouse, 142 Fulham Road, SW10 9QR

name: GOSH Sight and Sound Hospital & St Christophers Chapel
description: Visitors will be led on a tour of GOSH's newest redevelopment site, the Sight and Sound Hospital featuring a sensory garden and bespoke artworks. Tours will continue to the beautiful and unexpected St Christopher's chapel in the main site.
address: GOSH Sight and Sound Hospital, 40-41 Queen Square, WC1N 3AJ

name: Gaunson Creative Open Studios part of Markfield Road Festival
description: Gaunson Creative Studios in South Tottenham, home to over 70 artist studios, will be opening its doors for the first time since 2019. Visitors will be able to meet and buy from over 50 artists across the weekend.
address: Gaunson Creative Studios, Gunson House, Markfield Road, N15 4QQ

name: Grand Junction at St Mary Magdalene Church, Paddington
description: Grade I Victorian Gothic church by G E Street, architect of the Royal Courts of Justice. The recent conservation project reveals the majestic colours of Daniel Bell's painted ceiling, plus Dow Jones Architects' contemporary heritage wing.
address: Rowington Close, St Mary Magdalene's Church , W2 5TF

name: Greenwich Yacht Club
description: Contemporary timber and aluminium building using existing pier, offering unique views of the river, the O2 and the Thames Barrier.

name: Grow, Hackney
description: Repurposed out of a disused sausage factory, Grow was converted into a grassroots venue, community hub, bar and kitchen. This canalside venue is part of an ecosystem of artist studios & small independent businesses & working yard.
address: 98c Wallis Road, Main Yard, Hackney Wick, E9 5LN

name: Guided walk: Edward Harris Rabbits, and the development
description: E H Rabbits (1818-74) was a major contributor to the development of suburban Sutton.This linear walk will look at a number of the buildings he is associated with an other sites on the way to illustrate the Victorian development of Sutton.
address: Sutton Railway Station, High Street, Sutton, SM1 1JA

name: Guildhall Art Gallery
description:
Open daily 10.30am-4pm. 
Guided tours 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays, see below.
Home of the City of London's art collection, & remains of London's Roman Amphitheatre

name: Hackney School of Food
description:
Meet the Architects Tour
Hackney School of Food, Oswald Street, Lower Clapton, E5 0BT
9 September 1030-130pm
Tour of our award-winning kitchen & gardens led by our architects, Surman Weston and the team behind our food education hub.
address: Hackney School of Food, Oswald Street, E5 0BT

name: Hammersmith Quaker Meeting House
description: This new Quaker Meeting House is designed to be highly sustainable. It embodies the Quaker values of simplicity and equality, promoting a sense of calm.
address: 30-32 Bradmore Park Rd, London W6 0DT, W6 0DT

name: Havant House 53
description: A victorian mid terrace house with a dark blue exterior and a zany tiled front garden. Full of original features without being dictated by the era, colour continues inside with a yellow rubber floor in the kitchen.

name: Hinde Street Methodist Church
description: Hinde Street Methodist Church was constructed in 1887 with a grand pillared portico, spire and classical interior which remains largely unaltered. The entrance foyer was remodelled in 2014, to give the church a more welcoming appearance.

name: Historic & Modern Buildings in the City
description:
On this walk we will see many historic & modern buildings. see different architecture styles having regard to the environment and sustainability, and hear about famous architects, past and present.

Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square
description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass & bold sacred sculpture in what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake- Richmond & Christopher Whall.
address: 146 Sloane Street (just off Sloane Square), SW1X 9BZ

name: Honeywood Museum
description: Chalk and flint house dating to 17C with additions including extensions of 1896 and 1903 when owned by John Pattinson Kirk. Rich in period detail and the interior restored and stairs opened up with funding from the Heritage Lottery Fund.

name: Hornsey Library
description: Hornsey Library is a Grade II listed building, featuring Huxley-Jones' "Reclining figure" sculpture and the intricately etched glass "Hornsey window". A recent refurbishment has added practical updates while keeping the 1960s aesthetic.
address: Hornsey Library, Haringey Park, Haringey, N8 9JA

name: Housing in Kennington: A royal intervention
description: This walking tour around Kennington focuses on housing projects and particularly those developed by the Duchy Estate before and after World War I. The walk will provide an insight into the way public housing contributes to the mix of inhabitants in this sometimes forgotten area of London â€“ drawing comparisons in relation to London as a whole.
address: Outside Kennington Tube Station, Kennington Park Rd, SE11 4JQ

name: Huguenots' heritage in Spitalfields
description: Huguenots had a huge impact on Londonâ€™s culture, commerce and industry from the 17th century onwards. But how much do we really know about them? During this walk we will discover and explore the  history of Spitalfields.
address: Outside hub by Premier Inn London Spitalfield, 86 Brick Lane, E1 6RL

name: Industry and change through Hackney Wick
description: This walk focuses on industry, creativity and change in Hackney Wick and Fish Island, exploring how regeneration and gentrification have transformed the area.
address: Hackney Wick Overground Station, White Post Lane, E9 5TS

name: International Maritime Organization
description: The International Maritime Organization is a specialized agency of the UN, responsible for the safety and security of shipping and the prevention of marine pollution by ships. It is the only UN organization with headquarters in London.

name: Jonathan Tuckey Design Studio
description: This transformation of a derelict pub into an architecture studio doubles up as a gallery and lecture theatre. The new office is an example of the practiceâ€™s approach towards existing structures and intelligent architectural interventions.

name: Kempton Steam Museum
description: 1920s water pumping station comprising of several architectural styles. Interior retains original steam pumping machinery and historic electrical equipment.
address: Kempton Park Pumping Station, Snakey Lane, TW13 6XH

name: Kenwood
description: A striking Neoclassical villa in tranquil gardens on Hampstead Heath, Kenwood boasts breath-taking interiors by Robert Adam and a world-class art collection. For guaranteed entry, book your free ticket via the English Heritage website.

name: Kenworthy Road
description: This a new self-build house by two architect friends, Anthony Engi Meacock and Alexander Hills, on a narrow infill site within a late Victorian terrace.

name: King's Cross Heritage, Energy Centre and Garden Tours
description: King's Cross is a 67 acre development in Central London being transformed into a new city quarter with 20 regenerated heritage buildings, new homes, offices, public spaces, shops, galleries, bars, restaurants, schools and a university.
address: Western Transit Shed, 11 Stable Street, King's Cross, N1C 4AB

name: King's Cross Masterplan
description: The Kingâ€™s Cross Masterplan established a framework for the incremental redevelopment of this industrial heritage site through a mix of uses and a network of public spaces structuring new urban blocks and knitting the site into its context.

name: Kingston Guildhall and History Centre
description: Built in the Georgian style, the Guildhall brought together Kingston's administrative functions. Purpose-built Magistrates Courts were included in the building, part of which are now home to Kingston History Centre.
address: High Street , Kingston upon Thames, KT1 1EU

name: Kingston Historic walk
description:
We are running our usual guided walking tours around historic Kingston this year with reduced numbers.

Our guided tours are informative, interesting and fun. For more information about us visit: https://www.kingstontourguides.org.uk/
address: Market house, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 1JX

name: Kingston Library, Museum and Art Gallery
description: Adjoining Grade II listed Carnegie-funded library, museum and art gallery. Museum holdings range from ceramics to topographical drawings, including the collection left by Eadweard Muybridge, a native of Kingston and photographic pioneer.
address: Wheatfield Way, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 2PS

name: Lambeth Palace Library
description: A significant new redbrick addition to Londonâ€™s civic architecture, Lambeth Palace Library is the first new building on the site for 185 years and hosts the Church of Englandâ€™s archive.

name: Leathersellers' Hall
description: New Livery Hall behind a retained early 20th century faÃ§ade. This is the seventh Hall in the Leathersellers' Company's history since its foundation in the Middle Ages, and is located on the site of its second Hall.

name: Lexi Cinema
description: A contemporary extension to the Lexi Cinema, providing a 2nd screen. The building is a composition of brick and stainless steel; a nod to the parapets of surrounding terraces and reflecting the ever-changing sky above.

name: Limehouse Town Hall
description: Limehouse Town Hall is a building and resource for artists and cultural producers, audiences and communities from Tower Hamlets and beyond to share ideas, celebrate, organise, and imagine a better here and now.
address: Limehouse Town Hall, 646 Commercial Road, E14 7HA

name: Lincoln's Inn
description: Lincolnâ€™s Inn has been an association of barristers for over 600 years. An 11-acre site combining gardens with mediaeval, Victorian, Georgian, and modern buildings, including banqueting halls, a law library, a chapel, and teaching space.
address: The Honourable Society of Lincoln's Inn, WC2A 3QB

name: Little Mouse Cheese Shop
description: Visit Little Mouse, an Edwardian shop in South Norwood with original wooden frontage and fascia that is now an artisan cheesemonger.

name: Lockwood Way Industrial Estate - Architect-Led Tours
description: An architect-led tour of the recent public realm improvements. The tour will also provide a chance to look inside the tap rooms, scooter shop and winery and speak to the makers, brewers and winemakers on the estate about their processes.
address: Lockwood Way Industrial Estate, Walthamstow, E17 5RB

name: London Cable Car
description: Tour exploring the civil engineering achievements of the construction of the cable car. Led by the London Cable Car engineers* and front-of-house team.

name: London Fire Brigade Memorial Hall
description: Open Day: LFB's grade II listed Memorial Hall, part of the LFB's Headquarters, opened in 1937. The hall is rarely seen by the public & contains stunning large memorials by Gilbert Bayes commemorating firefighters lost protecting London.

name: London Museum, West Smithfield
description: Join us to find out more about our incredible journey to create a new museum for London. Apply to join a special tour of the General Market (currently in construction), or come along to meet the architects and take part in free family-friendly drop-in activities.
address: General Market Building, Charterhouse Street, EC1A 9LY

name: London Open Form Pavilion of Air
description: A floating roof of sound, GPS-triggered & accessed by headphones & Echoes app to playfully reframe public space as an essential community engagement. One of 15 in an international series drawing on Oskar & Zofia Hansenâ€™s Open Form concept.

name: London Scottish House (London Scottish Regimental Headquarters)
description: A Grade 2 listed former Territorial Army Drill Hall  featuring restored elements of the original 1882 design. It has a triple height central hall with the restored wrought iron balconies and roofing.  Notable Neo-Georgian design brickwork.
address: London Scottish House, 95 Horseferry Road, Westminster, SW1P 2DX

name: London's Roman Amphitheatre
description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm Closed Mon 19 September.
Combined guided tours of Amphitheatre and Guildhall Art Gallery at 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays.
The capitalâ€™s only known Roman Amphitheatre
address: Londonâ€™s Roman Amphitheatre at Guildhall Art Gallery, Guildhall Yard

name: Loop House, Teddington
description: Bridgeman Road project is a refurbishment project of a three-storey house with an extension of the roof with a dormer. The outcome is a joyful interior with bold use of colours and materials.

name: Lumley Chapel
description: Saxon and Medieval former chancel of parish church, preserved  after remainder was demolished in 1864. Part C11, with many important post-Reformation monuments, including those to the family of John, Lord Lumley of Nonsuch Palace.
address: St Dunstan's Churchyard, Church Road, Cheam, SM3 8QH

name: Manor Park Community Garden
description: Manor Park Community Garden was first established by local residents in 2012. . In 2020, a new group of residents saw an opportunity to reinvigorate the space, into an edible garden with fruit trees, asian vegetables and herbaceous flowers.

name: Maxwell House, Brackenbury Village
description: Maxwell House is a unique architecturally designed open-plan 4 storey home. Its design and tapestries are inspired by its rich history as a textile shop, & the Roberts family of drapers who lived there for 40yrs from the late 19th Century.

name: Moravian Close
description: A former stable yard of Sir Thomas More's Chelsea estate, now an 18C Chapel, other buildings, and burial ground. Parts of the enclosing walls are Tudor in origin. Ernest and Mary Gillick enhanced the grounds in the 20C.

name: Mother X Artists and Makers Open Studios
description: Mother X is a diverse group of artists, makers & creators that have inhabited a former Victorian chocolate factory in Hackney Wick for 15+ years. Come visit this unique building & see it's people & their work during the Open House Festival.
address: Floor D, Unit 9 Queen's Yard, Hackney Wick, E9 5EN

name: Museum of Croydon Behind the Scenes Tour
description: We propose to open the Museum of Croydon stores for an intimate guided tour of our stored collections also featuring an overview of collection care. This activity will take approximately 1hr and can cater for a maximum of 8 people.

name: National Liberal Club
description: An impressive Victorian neo-Classical building overlooking the Embankment of the river Thames. It is the second-largest clubhouse ever built, the first London building to incorporate a lift and to be entirely lit by electric lighting.

name: National Portrait Gallery Architecture Highlights Tours
description: Discover the architecture of the National Portrait Gallery, designed in 1896 by Ewan Christian and now transformed by Jamie Fobert Architects. Please meet at the Ross Street Entrance. Drop-in 16 & 17 September at specific times listed below.  But please note that spaces are extremely limited and tour places will be allocated on a first come, first served basis. Please arrive early to avoid disappointment.
address: National Portrait Gallery, St Martin's Place, WC2H 0HE

name: New Beacon Books
description: Specialist bookshop in African and Caribbean literature since 1966.
address: 76 Stroud Green Road, Finsbury Park, N4 3EN

name: Nunhead Cemetery
description: Magnificent Victorian cemetery with Gothic chapel & restored & ruined lodge. One of London's wildest cemeteries. Part restored with the help of a lottery grant. 52 acres of woodland, with bats, owls, foxes & squirrels. Grade II*  landscape.

name: Old Royal Naval College
description: Sir Christopher Wren's riverside masterpiece in Greenwich, built as the Royal Hospital for Seamen and begun in 1696.
address: Old Royal Naval College, Greenwich, SE10 9NN

name: Olympic Legacy Masterplan
description: Londonâ€™s 2012 Games provided a catalyst for regeneration in the Lower Lea Valley. Guided by the Legacy Masterplan, thousands of new homes and jobs are now being created, stitching together existing communities across the former floodplain.

name: One Canada Square, Canary Wharf Group (CWG) Marketing Suite
description: One of the most iconic structures dominating Londonâ€™s skyline, One Canada Square is the third tallest building in the UK. It is Canary Wharf Group's landmark tower which houses Europeâ€™s most influential FinTech scaler, Level39.
address: Meet: South Lobby, One Canada Square, Canary Wharf, E14 5AB

name: Open Havelock - guided visit
description: Open Havelock is a new community project on the Havelock Estate in Southall. The project transforms empty garages, undercrofts and their adjoining grounds into a flexible community facility situated off Willowbrook Road.

name: Our Yard at Clitterhouse Farm
description: Our Yard at Clitterhouse Farm is a community enterprise working to protect historic Victorian farm outbuildings and transform the site into a vibrant and sustainable community hub. Shortlisted for the Open City Stewardship Awards 2021.
address: Clitterhouse Playing Fields, Claremont Rd, NW2 1AP

name: Paddington Pantheon
description: The Paddington Pantheon is a restored and reimagined Mews House within a conservation area in West end London. We were commissioned by two artists to provide a series of gallery spaces within a rejuvenated and expanded family home.

name: Painters' Hall
description: Acquired in 1532 and rebuilt in 1670 after the Great Fire, the Hall was partially destroyed in 1941 by enemy action and rebuilt in a Neo-Georgian style in 1960. The original charter, portraiture and stained glass are of particular interest.

name: Patch, 42 York Street
description:
Patch is a pioneering neighbourhood workspace & culture venue in Twickenham.
Housed in a striking Art Deco building, formerly home to the South Eastern Electricity Board, itâ€™s a new local centre for work, cultural & community events.

name: Peer
description: Free access to the final weekend of 'we are a group of people composed of who we are', a survey exhibition that traces artistic, cultural and social collective work that took place in Hackney between 1971 and 1986.

name: People's Museum Somers Town
description:
A great little museum set in the Grade 2 listed Ossulston Estate - a prime example of pre-war Social housing - based on Karl Marz Hof in Vienna.
Open Wednesdays to Saturdays throughout Festival 
Sunday 11th Event

name: Phoenix Gardens Community Building
description: The first purpose-built new-build community centre to be built in the heart of Soho for generations, located within the renowned Phoenix Gardens. Winner: RIBA London Award. Designed by RIBA London Architect of the Year Winner.

name: Pope's Grotto
description: Grotto with mineral decoration is last remaining part of Alexander Pope's villa built 1720. The villa was demolished 1808 and replaced and redeveloped many times in following years but Pope's Grotto remains.
address: Radnor House School, Pope's Villa, Cross Deep, Twickenham, TW1 4QG

name: Poroban studio
description: Poroban is a multi-disciplinary design studio, based off Old Kent Road, specialising in low carbon building design. We are offering free design surgeries throughout September and are hosting an open day on Saturday 9th Sept.

name: Preedy Glass
description: An industrial building originally built for maintaining railways with a modern rear extension now housing a modern glass processing company

name: Present & Correct Stationers
description: Architecture for London designed and built a new home for stationers Present & Correct in a heritage retail unit. In a nod to the neighbouring British Museum, cabinets as 'wunderkammer' display the stationery as objects of desire.

name: Primrose Hill House
description: This 1960s house in Primrose Hill is a detached property in a Modernist estate of brick courtyard houses. Our project reconfigured the internal layout and added a rooftop extension, whilst improving the house's thermal performance.

name: Public art trail: Portraits of the South
description:
Public art trail: Portraits of the South by Abi Partington-Moran 

This innovative artist-created trail in Sutton Town Centre is the first of four Sutton STEAMS Ahead photographic commissions to be unveiled this Autumn/Winter.

name: Pushkin House
description: The independent cultural centre Pushkin House will contribute to this year's Open House Festival through a programme of events and community initiatives at its Grade-II listed building in Bloomsbury Square.

name: Quaker Meeting House - Brentford & Isleworth
description: Grade II* listed late-Georgian Quaker Meeting House (1785) set in garden with burial ground. Meeting room has wood panelling, elders' bench, upper gallery with drop shutters, and fine brickwork detailing. Contemporary brick boundary wall.

name: Quaker Meeting House - Wandsworth
description: Grade II listed, this is the oldest Quaker meeting house in London. Built in 1778, it has original panelling & a minister's gallery. See flagstones from the earlier 1674 buildings. Also a secluded burial ground & garden. Free refreshments.

name: RIBA
description: Fine example of Grade II* listed 1930s architecture with many original features and fittings and home to the world-class British Architectural Library collections.

name: Roca London Gallery
description: Designed by the world renowned Zaha Hadid Architects, Roca London Gallery is a unique space where water acts as the architectural theme. Guests can also visit 'Small Spaces in the City: Rethinking Inside the Box', a major exhibition exploring the challenges and innovative solutions for small live-and-work spaces in the city.

name: Romanian Cultural Institute
description: Situated in one of the largest and grandest 19th century squares in London, 1 Belgrave Square was acquired by Romania in 1936 and is now home to the Romanian Cultural Institute.

name: Rowley Way, Alexandra Road Estate - Residence
description: The Alexandra Road Estate is a low-rise, high-density, mixed-use development designed by Neave Brown for Camden's Architects' Department.

name: Royal Hospital for Neuro-disability
description: The original Grade II listed house was a former Georgian villa. 3 extensions were added through the Victorian period reflecting the style of the era.  Subsequent additions reflect medical practices. An archivist will be giving free tours.
address: Royal Hospital for Neuro-disability, West Hill, SW15 3SW

name: Royal Opera House
description: Home to The Royal Opera, The Royal Ballet and the Orchestra of the Royal Opera House, the ROH was reconfigured in 2018 by Stanton Williams to offer world-class performance spaces and a welcoming and inclusive cultural and social hub.

name: Sanitation and the City walking tour
description: From the Great Stink of London in 1858 to the Tideway 'Super Sewer' currently under construction, this walking tour will chart the development of London's sanitation infrastructure, past, present and future.
address: Outside the Lakeside Centre, Bazalgette Way, SE2 9AN

name: Saturday School: Quakers Hall
description: Assembled in the format and spirit of a Saturday School, this session, supported by Theatrum Mundi, will take place in the Croydon Quaker's Adult School Hall and support participants to map out spaces of care & resistance across Croydon.
address: The Adult School Hall, 60 Park Lane, CR0 1ER

name: Scadbury Moated Manor
description: See the archaeological excavations and Tudor foundations at Scadbury Moated Manor - which still has its moat around it.
address: Scadbury Moated Manor, Perry Street, Chislehurst, BR7 6LN

name: Senate House
description: Londonâ€™s tallest secular building when it opened as the HQ of the University of London and home to the Ministry of Information during WWII, this Grade II* listed landmark features Classicism and Art Deco elements.
address: University of London, Malet Street, WC1E 7HU

name: Shaftesbury Theatre
description: Built in a Renaissance style with high level Diocletian windows and a prominent grand cupola. In 2016 a new Fly Tower opened followed by remodelling of the auditorium in 2018 and the creation of a new basement space opening in the Autumn.

name: Shrewsbury House
description: Built in 1923, to replace its 18C namesake, Grade ll listed Shrewsbury House is the focus of the Shrewsbury Park Estate conservation area, built 1934-1936 by John Laing and Sons. Two Civil Defence centres are within the grounds.

name: Sitopia Farm
description: Sitopia Farm is a 2-acre organic and regenerative farm in the London Borough of Greenwich, producing vegetables, fruit and flowers for local people and businesses. We believe we can and should grow more food in the city/

name: Spruce House
description: Ao-ft co-founders', Liz Tatarintseva and Zach Fluker,  Spruce House and Studio is the pairâ€™s joint home in east Londonâ€™s Walthamstow. Not only has it been a personal labour of love, itâ€™s also the first flagship project of the practice owners' newly minted architecture practice.

name: St Anne's Church, Limehouse
description: St Anne's Limehouse has been described as 'the finest parish church in England.' Designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor, it is Grade I listed and one of the Major Churches in the Church of England. It is home to a thriving Christian congregation.

name: St Augustine of Canterbury
description: Victorian/Arts and Crafts church completed in 20C. Imposing west front by J Harold Gibbons with statuary by Dorothy Rope. Lady chapel by Henry Wilson. Stained glass by Margaret Aldridge Rope. Fine Hunter organ plus case.
address: Corner Archway Road & Langdon Park Road, N6 5BH

name: St Barnabas Church
description: Early English style, full of Pre-Raphaelite decoration. Important works by Bodley, Comper and Cundy and windows by Kempe and Tower. First Oxford Movement church. Recently restored 10 bell peal

name: St Bernard's Houses
description: 21 houses, in 3 terraces, built by Swiss architects Atelier 5 for Wates. Living areas on the upper floor are approached through a garden court. Bedrooms downstairs open to a lower garden. Pevsner wrote, 'a group with few equals in Britain'.
address: Meet: by OH banner, St Bernard's, Chichester Road, Croydon, CR0 5UL

name: St John on Bethnal Green
description: This grade one listed Sir John Soane church sits in the heart of the Bethnal Green in East London. Despite a fire in 1870, some original features remain. Visitors will have access to the church,  belfry, galleries and crypt.
address: St John on Bethnal Green, 200 Cambridge Heath Road, E2 9PA

name: St John the Divine
description: St Johnâ€™s has a wide nave approached via a narthex formed under the gallery running the width of the west end.  East of the nave is a chancel flanked to the south by the Lady Chapel and to the north by the organ chamber with loft over.

name: St John the Evangelist, Kingston upon Thames
description: The church is a large victorian building with an interesting beautiful interior. The foundation stone was laid in 1871 by Bishop Samuel Wilberforce, son of the anti-slavery campaigner, William.
address: Grove Lane, Kingston upon thames, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 2SU

name: St Lukeâ€™s Catholic Church, Pinner
description: A suburban post-war Catholic church built in a neo-Romanesque version of the continental modern style by Velarde, next to the original neo-gothic church from 1915, now a parish centre, and alongside the modernistic 1960s parish hall.

name: St Mary Magdalene
description: A historic living parish church, progressively shaped from the Tudor to the Edwardian period. St Mary's has recently undergone a major refurbishment and the newly restored windows recapture the original airiness of the C18 nave.

name: St Mary the Virgin
description: Small Grade I listed 12C chapel in lovely churchyard setting, it retains original architectural features and has interesting brasses, monuments and stained glass windows.
address: Church Road, Manor Park, Little Ilford, E12 6HA

name: St Mary's Church Bromley
description:
A plain Victorian Church set in a wooded Churchyard, with a vibrant and striking set of Murals around the altar and the Choir. 
Has indoor toilet facilities. 
A good quality well used organ in good condition, and an excellent accoustic
address: St Mary's Church, College Road, Bromley, BR1 3QG

name: St Mary's Church, Battersea
description: Classic Grade I listed Georgian church with outstanding interior and monuments. Renovated 2019/20.

name: St Matthew's Church
description:
St Matthews is Grade II listed, built 1883-4 and designed by the architect Alfred Jowers. 
It features a WW1 memorial screen designed by Reginald Hallward and stained glass some believed to be by Edward Frampton
address: St Matthews church, North Common Road, W5 2QA

name: St Nicholas Church
description: Built in the Gothic style with dressed flint and stone dressings. There are monuments to Joseph Glover (1628), Lady Dorothy Brownlow (1699), William Earl Talbot (1782) and Isaac Littlebury (1740). The churchyard has 5 Grade II tombs.

name: St Paul's, Newington
description: Modern architecture church with large copper and lead roof and concrete, brick and stained glass external structure. Marble, wood and plaster interior and artwork by Sculptor Freda Pinto and Gerald Holtom.

name: Stanley Arts
description: A public hall, theatre and gallery in grand Edwardian style. Grade II listed, Stanley made fun of the Victorian style with grand ornamentation. It reflects Stanley's interest in science, the arts and public cultural improvement.

name: Stories fromâ€¦The Welsh Chapel
description: An exhibition exploring the rapid technological changes in transport in the Sutton New Town Area (1870-1911). The Welsh Chapel is part of the Presbyterian Church of Wales - originally built as a Primitive Methodist Chapel in 1879.
address: Lind Road, Sutton, Greater London, SM1 4PJ

name: Streamline in the Suburb
description:
A walking tour exploring the 1930s Streamline Moderne architecture of Hampstead Garden Suburb, led by Joe Mathieson of the Hampstead Garden Suburb Trust. 

1 of 3 walks run by the Trust.

name: Streatham Space Project Family Day
description: A free family day out for the littleuns, bigguns and middleuns! Come see our unique, purpose built live arts venue, and enjoy some of the free family activities on offer. Streatham Space Project is neighbourhood arts venue and charity.

name: Sugar House Island
description: Sugar House Island is a brand-new 26 acre mixed use neighbourhood of homes, offices, creative spaces, retail, education and public outdoor space.  The development combines modern architecture with retained heritage features. This incudes Talent House, a new state-of-the-art creative hub for next generation of music and dance professionals, and is supported by the Mayor of London.
address: Vastint UK, 135 High Street, Stratford, E15 2RB

name: T J Boulting
description: Red brick and Portland stone corner building with three prominent signs in Arts & Craft style lettering in green and gold mosaic for the company 'TJ Boulting & Sons'.

name: Talks at The Thorney Island Society Archives
description: Victor Keegan, author of two acclaimed books on Lost London, asks how the streets around the Thorney Island Society Archives in Old Pye Street could have been so lawless and deprived, so close to Westminster Abbey and Parliament.

name: Temple Bar
description: Temple Bar is a 350 year old gateway to the City of London, designed by Sir Christopher Wren. It formerly stood in Fleet Street, and was the last surviving gateway to the City of London.
address: First Floor, Paternoster Lodge, 2 Paternoster Square, EC4M 7DX

name: The Africa Centre
description: A 1960s former office block that has been transformed into a vibrant cultural hub showcasing the best of contemporary African culture and heritage. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.

name: The Association of Anaesthetists and Anaesthesia Heritage Centre
description: Grade II listed building with neoclassical portico. Highly decorated meeting rooms throughout the building with ceiling and wall mouldings, and artwork featuring Venus the Goddess of Love and the Greek Muses.

name: The Barbican & The City Gardens
description: Built on the site destroyed by The Blitz during the World War II, The Barbican Estate is a fascinating area and an icon of Brutalist architecture. Architects were Chamberlain, Powell and Bon,  We  will also visit several amazing gardens.

name: The Cumberland Hotel
description: Discover the breathtaking interior of London's iconic 1700s landmark, The Cumberland Hotel. Immerse yourself in its rich artistic history, once home to renowned artists. Join us to experience the allure of this extraordinary venue.
address: The Cumberland Hotel, Great Cumberland Place, W1H 7DL

name: The Department Store
description: The Department Store is an award winning refurbishment of a dilapidated Edwardian building in Brixton, completed by Squire and Partners in 2017. The design was informed by the layers of history and existing fabric of the heritage building.
address: The Department Store, 248 Ferndale Road, SW9 8FR

name: The Earls Court Development Company
description: Learn about our plans to transform this 40-acre site into a largely car free mixed use development that aims to go beyond net zero and bring the wonder back to Earls Court
address: Earls Court Project Rooms, 16-18 Empress Place, SW6 1TT

name: The Egypt Exploration Society (EES)
description: The EES is a charity supporting and promoting Egyptian cultural heritage located in 3-4 Doughty Mews. We propose an Open Day on Saturday 9th September with collections tours and an exhibition of the history and archaeology of the building.
address: The Egypt Exploration Society, 3-4 Doughty Mews, WC1N 2PG

name: The Gilbert & George Centre
description: The Gilbert & George Centre was originally established as a registered charity by the artist in 2009 with the objective to advance the education of the public in the arts, and generally to advance the arts, architecture, heritage and culture for the benefit of the public.

name: The Great Barn, Harmondsworth
description: The timbers of this great medieval barn (1426-7), over 190 feet long and nearly 40 feet high, are 95% original. Displays include the conservation/repairs carried out in 2014 and its place in the agricultural history of the village.
address: Manor Court, High Street, Harmondsworth, UB7 0AQ

name: The Great Fire of London
description:
In 1666, the conflagration devastated most of the City, thousands of houses, many churches and St Paul's Cathedral destroyed. Christopher Wren played a major role in rebuilding the City. 
Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: The Life Cycle of London's Landscape
description:
The life cycle of Londonâ€™s landscape starts with history. History becomes an integral part of it from the very inception of its design, enriched through construction, and expands even after the buildingâ€™s completion. As architectural landscapes are repurposed for contemporary needs, they continue to respond to challenges and stigmas of marginalised communities. 

Join us on Saturday 9th September (11am-1pm) to discuss what happens when people inhabit landscapes and new communities emerge. 

As landscapes mature, we are given a choice: to ignore or embrace what came before.

What happens when the histories of these communities are neglected?
address: Aga Khan Centre, 10 Handyside Street, N1C 4DN

name: The Listening Space Garden
description: We are a community-led garden in the heart of an urban general practice. The garden has been our seedbed and hothouse allowing us to widen the traditional prescription beyond pills and procedures

name: The Making of Pimlico
description: A walking tour exploring  the work of early 19th century master-builder, Mr Cubitt. Explores how the area has changed and been shaped by some of the important and influential planning, housing and design ideas of its time.
address: Pimlico Tube station - Rampayne Street entrance street level.

name: The Marshall Building - London School of Economics and Political Science
description: A large multi-purpose building occupying a pivotal position at the southern corner of Lincolnâ€™s Inn Fields.  The building provides state of the art, flexible teaching spaces on the lower levels and faculty accommodation on the upper levels.
address: The Marshall Building, 44 Lincoln's Inn Fields, WC2A 3PF

name: The Mysterious Black Tudors - Westminster Family Trail
description: Celebrate the Open House Festival with this fun and interactive family event about Britain's forgotten history of the Black Tudors.

name: The National Archives
description: South West London's hidden Brutalist masterpiece.
address: Ruskin Avenue, Kew, Richmond, Surrey, TW9 4DU

name: The Questors Theatre
description: Originally planned in 1954, the first new theatre after the war, the Questors Playhouse opened in 1964, by which time its design had been followed by the Chichester Festival Theatre and the Crucible, Sheffield.
address: The Questors Theatre, 12 Mattock Lane, W5 5BQ

name: The Round House
description: Grade II* listed late Georgian elliptical 3-storey stuccoed villa.

name: The Swedenborg Society
description: Grade II-listed Georgian domestic building c.1760, formerly part of Bedford Estate. Interior refurbished 1924-5 to form lecture hall (restored 2014), library, bookshop and offices. Oak woodwork and green Doulton tiles line the staircase.

name: Thornhill Square
description: A tour of one of the largest and best preserved early Victorian squares and gardens in London, also with a magnificent and original public library of 1906, which shows Byzantine and Art Nouveau influences, and a remarkable Gothic church.
address: Meet outside the main door of St Andrewâ€™s Church, Bridgeman Road

name: Timothy Hatton Architects â€“ The Foundry
description: Tucked behind a busy road in W12, this former foundry is a multi-level development featuring an architectsâ€™ studio with courtyards and spaces for exhibitions and musical performances. The  building's 15m brick chimney is a local landmark.

name: Tin House
description: Making efficient use of an irregular urban site, this house is made up of interconnecting top-lit pavilions arranged to define a tranquil private courtyard.

name: Tommy Flowers at Chartwell Court (ex Post Office Research Station Dollis Hill)
description: Former research establishment where Tommy Flowers built Colossus, the world's first programmable electronic computer in 1943. Blue plaque to be unveiled on 6 Sep 2023
address: Chartwell Court, 151 Brook Rd, Neasden, NW2 7DW

name: Tour of Convoys Wharf
description: We will open our site for a walking tour around our historic former naval dockyard, which will soon be transformed into a modern redevelopment. Learn about our historic Olympia Building and the former Deptford Dockyard.

name: Tour the Square Root Factory
address: Unit D11, Leyton Industrial Village, Argall Avenue, E10 7QP

name: Tower Hamlets Town Hall
description: Tower Hamlets Town Hall, the new headquarters for the London Borough of Tower Hamlets Council, encompasses the restoration of the Grade II listed former Royal London Hospital building, and the addition of a new build extension.

name: Trellick Tower
description: Goldfinger's 31-storey social housing tower is one of London's most remarkable high-rises. Monumental, with its free-standing service tower and triumphal boiler house, Trellick retains beautiful detailing and a rich use of materials.

name: Trevithick House
description: Pre war social housing flats, red brick, Georgian sash windows, playground, allotments and washing lines outside.

name: Turf Projects (Whitgift Centre)
description: Founded in 2013 by Croydon locals, Turf Projects is Croydonâ€™s homegrown artist space and the first entirely artist-run contemporary art space in the borough.
address: 46-47 Trinity Court, Whitgift Centre, Croydon, CR0 1UQ

name: Twickenham Museum
description: Grade II listed former waterman's cottage c1720. Restored and converted into a museum celebrating the rich history of Twickenham, Whitton, Teddington and the Hamptons.

name: Tyrants, Colonialism and Slavery walking tour
description: A diverse walking tour, with a qualified guide, in the heart of Westminster where we visit some statues and places that have a significance to tyranny, colonialism and slavery.  The walk is accessible to all and ends in Trafalgar Square.

name: UCL PEARL
description: UCL PEARL is a brand new building designed to be a laboratory that can "house the world" so that we can create different environments from around the world for experiments about people and the environment around them.
address: UCL PEARL, Yew Tree Avenue, RM10 7FN

name: Union Chapel
description:
A Grade I and II*  treasure thatâ€™s home to an inclusive church, an award winning venue, a unique organ and The Margins Project for those in crisis in London. 
Family Organ Building Workshops are generously supported by the Institute of Physics

name: Valence House
description: Grade II* listed 15C and later manor house with medieval moat. Recently discovered late 16C wall painting and impressive oak paneling. Evocative museum galleries that bring Barking & Dagenham's past alive.

name: Vanbrugh Park Estate
description: Vanbrugh Park Estate was designed by Chamberlin, Powell and Bon. The estate shares many stylistic similarities with their wider work such as the semi-circular curved motifs, purposeful use of light, and approach to community living.
address: 18 Combe Avenue, Vanbrugh Park Estate, SE3 7PY

name: Walking Tour of Wood Green Placemaking Projects
description: Haringey Council will guide the public around recently completed placemaking projects around Wood Green town centre, featuring the new Youth Hub, a new Community Cafe in a park and co-designed art murals and pocket parks
address: Outside Wood Green Underground Station, N22 8HH

name: Walking tour: Central Foundation Boys' School
description: Over the last 13 years, the 150-year-old school has reused and built upon its existing campus to provide new, state-of-the-art facilities. See how new architecture can sit with heritage buildings to create something completely new.
address: Central Foundation Boys School, Cowper St, EC2A 4SH

name: Walthamstow Wetlands
description: Join us for a tour of the refurbished Marine Engine House with our architects Witherford Watson Mann.
address: Marine Engine House, 2 Forest Road, N17 9NH

name: Walworth Garden
description: Our timber frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism-the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction, into a thriving community garden

name: Wandsworth House
description:
A refurbishment of the loft. Two extra rooms are added accessible from a shared room. A lounge netting hangs in front of the loft spaces. 
A refurbishment of the lower ground floor into a home office with its own entrance.

name: West Wickham Library
description: Art Deco building designed in 1934 by Leslie Kemp and Tasker in International Moderne style. Now the temporary home of West Wickham Library.

name: Westbury Estate
description: Westbury Estate was designed by Philip Bottomley and Colin Lucas in 1961 - 1966 under Ted Hollamby. The resident-led walk will include a discussion about regeneration as well as audio recordings from Philip Bottomley tbc

name: Whitehall Historic House
description: Originally a farmer's house dating to 1500, with jettied upper storey. Later additions reflect the changing lifestyles of the owners, including the Killicks for over two centuries. Now houses scale model of Henry VIII's Nonsuch Palace.

name: Wiener Holocaust Library
description: Sensitive yet bold refurbishment of historic Grade II listed townhouse for The Wiener Library including dramatic first floor reading room, mezzanine and ground floor exhibition spaces.

name: William Morris Society - Kelmscott House
description: Residence of Sir Francis Ronalds, George MacDonald and (from 1878-96) William Morris. Organised by William Morris Society. Access to The William Morris Society's premises in the Coach House and basement only, includes current exhibition.

name: Wimbledon Windmill
description: Rare example of a hollow post mill (1817). Grade II* listed, it now contains a museum depicting the history and development of windmills in Britain. Many working models, windmill machinery, equipment and tools.

name: Zoroastrian Centre For Europe (formerly Grosvenor Cinema)
description: Grade II* listed Art Deco building with well-preserved interior. Auditorium with deep coved ribs; proscenium arch flanked by fluted columns. Restoration fully funded by  donations from Zoroastrian faith community, without government grants.
